<p>

<b>Midori</b> is the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../198/308198.xml">
code name</link> for a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../801/1750801.xml">
managed code</link> <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../194/22194.xml">
operating system</link> being developed by <physical_entity wordnetid="100001930" confidence="0.8">
<military_unit wordnetid="108198398" confidence="0.8">
<person wordnetid="100007846" confidence="0.8">
<division wordnetid="108213205" confidence="0.8">
<causal_agent wordnetid="100007347" confidence="0.8">
<scientist wordnetid="110560637" confidence="0.8">
<army_unit wordnetid="108190754" confidence="0.8">
<research_worker wordnetid="110523076" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../522/2163522.xml">
Microsoft Research</link></research_worker>
</army_unit>
</scientist>
</causal_agent>
</division>
</person>
</military_unit>
</physical_entity>
. It has been reported<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%221%22])">1</ref><ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%222%22])">2</ref> to be a possible commercial implementation of the <O wordnetid="106832680" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../655/2049655.xml">
Singularity</link></O>
 operating system, a research project started in 2003 to build a highly-<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../384/661384.xml">
dependable</link> operating system in which the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../394/50394.xml">
kernel</link>, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../101/9101.xml">
device driver</link>s, and applications are all written in managed code. It was designed for concurrency, and can run applications in multiple places.<weblink xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.sdtimes.com/link/32627">
http://www.sdtimes.com/link/32627</weblink> It also features an entirely new security model that sandboxes applications for increased security.<weblink xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.sdtimes.com/MICROSOFT_S_MIDORI_TO_SANDBOX_APPS_FOR_INCREASED_SECURITY/About_SECURITY_and_MICROSOFT/32662">
http://www.sdtimes.com/MICROSOFT_S_MIDORI_TO_SANDBOX_APPS_FOR_INCREASED_SECURITY/About_SECURITY_and_MICROSOFT/32662</weblink> Microsoft has mapped out several possible migration paths from Windows to Midori.<weblink xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.sdtimes.com/MICROSOFT_MAPS_OUT_MIGRATION_FROM_WINDOWS/About_VIRTUALIZATION_and_WINDOWS_and_MICROSOFT/32646">
http://www.sdtimes.com/MICROSOFT_MAPS_OUT_MIGRATION_FROM_WINDOWS/About_VIRTUALIZATION_and_WINDOWS_and_MICROSOFT/32646</weblink>. In a possible link to Microsoftâ€™s Oslo composite application initiative, the programming model will have a dependence on metadata, with the aim of allowing the system to more reliably manage applications. <weblink xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="http://www.sdtimes.com/link/32957">
http://www.sdtimes.com/link/32957</weblink></p>
<p>

The code name <it>Midori</it> was first discovered through the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../229/77229.xml">
PowerPoint</link> presentation <it>CHESS: A systematic testing tool for concurrent software</it>.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%223%22])">3</ref></p>
<p>

Midori has also been rumoured by some IT journalists as a possible replacement to <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../890/18890.xml">
Microsoft Windows</link>.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%222%22])">2</ref></p>

